data.title: Wikibooks, open books for an open world
data.text:
Rates are from 1-10:

(?) = can't remember, (Q) = quit in the middle, (8-9) - you shouldn't die without reading those, (5-7) - pretty cool, (3-4) - mediocre

My rating is based on many factors, most important to me is the level of imagination or new concepts a work introduces without getting turned into dreamscapes. Secondly how intelligent the author is in advancing the plot in a plausible way without boring the reader to death. I don't like mundane story lines or overcomplicated concepts or very convoluted mental or moral dilemmas, if pieces don't fit well together I will not like it, I'm willing to turn off the reality/science verifier if the history is entertaining, a capacity one must have if one enjoys only books and has a good imagination.

I have read many more books I will try to tag the ones I remember or came across with a "?" until I revisit the text and rate it. Also if I quit ("q") a book it was because the history was boring or very confusing or just didn't catch my interest I will rate the work as for what I did read so classification may be off by one point above what I would rank it if I spent the time to really find out. I rarely skip to the end of the book in that event, if I quit its because I just don't care what happens next. This is important as low ranking books if finished indicate a good plot line.

User:Alexsmail keeps a similar page in User:Alexsmail/What to read if anyone else does have and maintain a similar page let me know about it...
